exports[`Functions — core formatting > flip (function manipulation) 1`] = `
"# flip()

> **flip**\\<\`First\`, \`Second\`, \`Rest\`, \`Result\`\\>(\`fn\`): (\`b\`, \`a\`, ...\`rest\`) => \`Result\`

Creates a function with its first two arguments reversed.


---

## Type Parameters

### First: \`First\`

The first argument type.

### Second: \`Second\`

The second argument type.

### Rest: \`Rest extends unknown[]\`

The remaining argument types.

### Result: \`Result\`

The return type.

---

## Parameters

### fn: \`(a, b, ...rest) => Result\`

The function to flip.

---

## Returns

The flipped function.


---

## Since

2.0.0

---

## Also known as

<AlsoKnownAs data={{"lodash":{"name":"flip","group":"Function"},"ramda":{"name":"flip","group":"Function"},"radashi":{"name":"flip","group":"Curry"},"remeda":{"name":"flip","group":"Function"},"moderndash":null,"antfu":null,"effect":{"name":"flip","group":"Function"},"es-toolkit":{"name":"flip","group":"compat"},"python":null,"kotlin":null}} />


---

## Example

\`\`\`typescript
const divide = (a: number, b: number) => a / b;
const divideBy = flip(divide);

divide(10, 2);   // => 5
divideBy(2, 10); // => 5
\`\`\`

---

## How it works?

Creates a function with its first two arguments reversed.
<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    subgraph "Original: divide(a, b)"
        A1["divide(10, 2)"] --> B1["10 ÷ 2 = 5"]
    end\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    subgraph "Original: divide(a, b)"
        A1["divide(10, 2)"] --> B1["10 ÷ 2 = 5"]
    end\`}
/>

<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    subgraph "Flipped: divideBy(b, a)"
        A2["divideBy(2, 10)"] --> B2["10 ÷ 2 = 5"]
    end\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    subgraph "Flipped: divideBy(b, a)"
        A2["divideBy(2, 10)"] --> B2["10 ÷ 2 = 5"]
    end\`}
/>

### Argument Swap
<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    A["fn(a, b, ...rest)"] --> B["flip(fn)"]
    B --> C["fn(b, a, ...rest)"]\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    A["fn(a, b, ...rest)"] --> B["flip(fn)"]
    B --> C["fn(b, a, ...rest)"]\`}
/>

---

## Use Cases

### Create natural APIs 📌

Reverse function parameters to create more intuitive and readable function interfaces.
Essential for API design and improving code readability.

<div style={{display: 'flex', flexWrap: 'wrap', gap: '8px', marginTop: '8px', marginBottom: '16px'}}>
  <a href="/use-cases?q=natural" style={{
                    display: 'inline-block',
                    padding: '2px 8px',
                    borderRadius: '12px',
                    backgroundColor: 'var(--ifm-color-emphasis-100)',
                    color: 'var(--ifm-color-content)',
                    textDecoration: 'none',
                    fontSize: '0.85em',
                    border: '1px solid var(--ifm-color-emphasis-200)'
                }}>#natural</a>
  <a href="/use-cases?q=APIs" style={{
                    display: 'inline-block',
                    padding: '2px 8px',
                    borderRadius: '12px',
                    backgroundColor: 'var(--ifm-color-emphasis-100)',
                    color: 'var(--ifm-color-content)',
                    textDecoration: 'none',
                    fontSize: '0.85em',
                    border: '1px solid var(--ifm-color-emphasis-200)'
                }}>#APIs</a>
  <a href="/use-cases?q=parameters" style={{
                    display: 'inline-block',
                    padding: '2px 8px',
                    borderRadius: '12px',
                    backgroundColor: 'var(--ifm-color-emphasis-100)',
                    color: 'var(--ifm-color-content)',
                    textDecoration: 'none',
                    fontSize: '0.85em',
                    border: '1px solid var(--ifm-color-emphasis-200)'
