exports[`Functions — core formatting > negate (higher-order) 1`] = `
"# negate()

> **negate**\\<\`Args\`\\>(\`predicate\`): (...\`args\`) => \`boolean\`

Creates a function that negates the result of the predicate.


---

## Type Parameters

### Args: \`Args extends unknown[]\`

The argument types of the predicate.

---

## Parameters

### predicate: \`(...args) => unknown\`

The predicate to negate.

---

## Returns

The new negated function.


---

## Since

2.0.0

---

## Also known as

<AlsoKnownAs data={{"lodash":{"name":"negate","group":"Function"},"ramda":{"name":"complement","group":"Logic"},"radashi":null,"remeda":null,"moderndash":null,"antfu":null,"effect":{"name":"not","group":"Boolean"},"es-toolkit":{"name":"negate","group":"function"},"python":null,"kotlin":null}} />


---

## Example

\`\`\`typescript
const isEven = (n: number) => n % 2 === 0;
const isOdd = negate(isEven);

isOdd(1); // => true
isOdd(2); // => false

// Use with array methods
[1, 2, 3, 4, 5].filter(negate(isEven));
// => [1, 3, 5]

// With multiple arguments
const includes = (arr: number[], val: number) => arr.includes(val);
const excludes = negate(includes);
excludes([1, 2, 3], 4); // => true
\`\`\`

---

## How it works?

Creates a function that returns the logical negation of the predicate result.
<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    A["isEven(4)"] --> B["true"]
    C["negate(isEven)(4)"] --> D["false"]\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    A["isEven(4)"] --> B["true"]
    C["negate(isEven)(4)"] --> D["false"]\`}
/>

### Transformation
<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    subgraph "Original"
        A1["predicate(x)"] --> B1["true/false"]
    end
    subgraph "Negated"
        A2["negate(predicate)(x)"] --> B2["!result"]
    end\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    subgraph "Original"
        A1["predicate(x)"] --> B1["true/false"]
    end
    subgraph "Negated"
        A2["negate(predicate)(x)"] --> B2["!result"]
    end\`}
/>

### Array Filter Example
<ResponsiveMermaid
  desktop={\`flowchart LR
    A["[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]"] --> B["filter(negate(isEven))"]
    B --> C["[1, 3, 5]"]\`}
  mobile={\`flowchart TB
    A["[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]"] --> B["filter(negate(isEven))"]
    B --> C["[1, 3, 5]"]\`}
/>

---

## Use Cases

### Filter Inversion for array operations 📌

Invert predicates for filtering operations.
Essential for creating opposite filter conditions.

